      "side": 1,
      "message": "Hmm, even on Windows, it is better to use python path found from $PATH by default as I assume that most users installed their python via recommended way from their organization. And they still get the same absolute path like `/usr/bin/python` on POSIX?\n\nIf you want to use relative path, is it possible to use \nhttps://gn.googlesource.com/gn/+/refs/heads/main/docs/reference.md#var_python_path:~:text\u003dhelp%20%2D%2Droot%2Dpattern%22)-,script_executable,-%5Boptional%5D%0A%20%20%20%20%20%20By%20default\nin your `.gn` file?",
      "revId": "f27f9c5db59999f9b87196bac4f11f3cb0e82309",
      "serverId": "c360c8e5-7aa8-3905-a7a0-810934766dac"
    },
    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "603355fa_b4739cce",
        "filename": "/COMMIT_MSG",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 9,
      "author": {
        "id": 1001787
      },
      "writtenOn": "2025-11-11T06:36:20Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Even when setting relative path using `python_path` in `.gn`, the python path stored inside `BuildSettings` will always be an absolute path due to this:\nhttps://gn.googlesource.com/gn/+/refs/heads/main/src/gn/setup.cc#353\n\nRegarding using the python path in $PATH, there are a few issues with this:\n\n1) it will not work with remote execution because the user may have python in any  arbitrary $PATH that does not match what\u0027s available on the remote worker.  Note that because GN *always* makes `python_path` absolute on Windows (see link above), we are unable to simply use `\"python.exe\"` and let $PATH figure it out.\n\n2) organizations that work on many different projects will have multiple versions of python being used, so it becomes much easier to place the appropriate python inside each project.  For example, chromium can do this in `src/third_party/depot_tools`",
      "parentUuid": "296e159b_5d04d181",
      "revId": "f27f9c5db59999f9b87196bac4f11f3cb0e82309",
      "serverId": "c360c8e5-7aa8-3905-a7a0-810934766dac"
    },
